				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">...its worse than rom because it's too slow.</div><br />Reading is the same speed. If you have enough RAM to cover your bankswitching needs, fill it up once at some appropriate transition, and switching is just as fast as with ROM.<br /><br />Writing is bandwidth-limited, but if you're comparing to ROM's write speed, it's infinitely faster. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /> It's only &quot;slow&quot; if you're comparing non-bankswitched RAM writes to ROM bankswitching.<br /><br />The problem here is more with the iNES format than anything else. Now that RAM is as cheap as it is, it's pretty viable to build a board with bankswitching RAM. Emulator support requires iNES 2 headers, though, which is still poorly adopted.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

